      { q: "Which fountain is quieter?", a: "The PETKIT Eversweet is noticeably quieter at just 30dB — about the volume of a whisper. The Catit PIXI runs around 35dB, still quiet but you'll hear the water flow more distinctly. If the fountain is in a bedroom or quiet home office, PETKIT is the clear winner." },
      { q: "Is the Catit PIXI's water intake tracking useful?", a: "For health-conscious owners, yes — the PIXI's app estimates how much your cat drinks based on pump activity and water level changes. This can help detect early signs of kidney issues or diabetes, which are common in older cats. However, it's an estimate, not a precise measurement. If your cat has health concerns, it's a valuable extra layer of monitoring." },
      { q: "Which has cheaper long-term filter costs?", a: "PETKIT's multi-layer filters cost about $25-35/year (replacing every 4-6 weeks). Catit PIXI's filters run $40-55/year. Over 3 years, that's roughly a $45-60 difference — enough to nearly buy another PETKIT fountain. However, both are far cheaper than the cost of treating a dehydrated cat's urinary issues." },
      { q: "Do cats prefer one fountain over the other?", a: "The Catit PIXI has a unique advantage: 3 different drinking heights (stream, pool, and waterfall) that accommodate kittens, adult cats, and seniors in one fountain. The PETKIT's single-stream design is simpler. Most cats will drink from either, but multi-cat homes with cats of different sizes will find the PIXI's ergonomic design more universally accessible." },
    ],
  },
  "petlibro-vs-petkit": {
    title: "Petlibro Granary vs PETKIT Fresh Element (2026) — Camera Feeder or Freshness First?",
    description: "Petlibro Granary Camera Feeder vs PETKIT Fresh Element Solo head-to-head. We compare camera capability, food freshness, app experience, capacity, and which $130-140 smart feeder is the right pick for your pet.",
    winner: "The Petlibro Granary wins for anxious pet parents who want to see their cat eating — the built-in 1080p camera with night vision and motion alerts effectively replaces a separate pet camera ($30-100 value). But the PETKIT Fresh Element wins on food preservation with its superior rotary sealing system, easier disassembly for cleaning, and more reliable kibble dispensing. At just $10 apart, this isn't about price — it's about whether you value visual check-ins (Petlibro) or food freshness and cleaning ease (PETKIT).",
    productAId: "petlibro-granary",
    productBId: "petkit-fresh-element",
    comparisonRows: [
      ["Price", "$139", "$129"],
      ["Rating", "★★★★½ (4.5)", "★★★★⅖ (4.4)"],
      ["Reviews", "8,700+", "6,100+"],
      ["Camera", "1080p + Night Vision + Motion Alerts", "None"],
      ["Two-Way Audio", "Yes", "No"],
      ["Capacity", "3L or 5L", "4L"],
      ["Food Preservation", "Standard hopper + desiccant", "Rotary sealing system (superior)"],
      ["Meals Per Day", "Up to 10", "Up to 10"],
      ["Cleaning", "Hopper and bowl detach", "Fully detachable, dishwasher-safe"],
      ["Battery Backup", "No (sold separately)", "No (sold separately)"],
      ["Warranty", "1 year", "1 year"],
    ],
    faqs: [
      { q: "Is the Petlibro camera worth sacrificing food freshness?", a: "For most owners, yes — the camera is genuinely useful. You can confirm your pet ate, check food levels remotely, and get motion alerts if your pet approaches the feeder. However, the PETKIT's rotary seal really does keep kibble fresher longer, especially in humid climates. If you live in a dry climate and want visual peace of mind, Petlibro. If you live somewhere humid and care most about food quality, PETKIT." },
      { q: "Which feeder is easier to clean?", a: "The PETKIT Fresh Element is noticeably easier to clean. Its hopper, bowl, and internal components all detach completely and many parts are dishwasher-safe. The Petlibro's camera module makes disassembly slightly more involved — you need to be careful around the lens. If deep cleaning is a priority, PETKIT wins." },
      { q: "Which app is better — Petlibro or PETKIT?", a: "Both apps are solid, but Petlibro's is more polished and camera-focused — the live feed loads fast and motion alerts are reliable. PETKIT's app is functional but feels more utilitarian, with good feeding logs and low-food alerts. For the camera experience, Petlibro wins. For pure feeding management, they're comparable." },
      { q: "Can either feeder handle large kibble?", a: "Both handle standard dry kibble up to about 15mm. The PETKIT's rotary mechanism can occasionally jam with irregularly shaped or very large kibble. The Petlibro's gravity-fed design is slightly more forgiving with odd-shaped kibble. If your pet eats large or irregular kibble, Petlibro is the safer bet." },
    ],
  },
  "tractive-vs-nofee-gps": {
    title: "Tractive GPS vs No-Fee GPS Tracker (2026) — Subscription or One-Time Purchase?",
    description: "Tractive GPS LTE ($79 + $5-13/month) vs No Monthly Fee GPS Tracker ($33, zero fees). We compare coverage, accuracy, battery life, and which GPS tracker offers the best long-term value.",
    winner: "The Tractive GPS LTE wins for most dog owners who need reliable, global tracking — the subscription is worth it for the superior coverage, longer battery life, and polished app. The No-Fee GPS tracker is the budget champion for owners who absolutely refuse subscriptions and need basic tracking in areas with good cell coverage. At $33 with zero recurring costs, it's a remarkable value — just don't expect premium features. If your dog is a high-risk escape artist, pay the Tractive subscription. If you just want basic peace of mind on a budget, the No-Fee tracker works.",
    productAId: "tractive-gps",
    productBId: "nofee-gps-tracker",
    comparisonRows: [
      ["Price", "$79 upfront", "$33 upfront"],
      ["Subscription", "$5-13/month", "None — zero"],
      ["3-Year Total Cost", "$259-547", "$33"],
      ["Coverage", "170+ countries (global)", "US/Canada (cellular-based)"],
      ["Battery Life", "2-5 days", "1-2 days"],
      ["Waterproof", "Yes (IPX7)", "Splash resistant only"],
      ["Weight", "26g (under 1 oz)", "20g (very light)"],
      ["App Quality", "Excellent, polished", "Basic, occasional glitches"],
      ["Virtual Fence", "Yes, reliable", "Yes, but less precise"],
      ["Warranty", "2 years", "1 year"],
    ],
    faqs: [
      { q: "Which is cheaper over 3 years — Tractive or No-Fee?", a: "The No-Fee tracker wins easily: $33 total vs $259-547 for Tractive depending on your plan. But the Tractive gives you better coverage, longer battery life, and a more reliable app. It's like comparing a $33 prepaid phone to a $79 phone with a $10/month plan — the prepaid is cheaper, but you get what you pay for." },
      { q: "Does the No-Fee tracker really have zero hidden costs?", a: "Yes — there's genuinely no SIM card, no activation fee, no monthly plan. The manufacturer covers the cellular data through their own bulk carrier agreement. The catch: they can change this policy at any time, and the build quality reflects the $33 price point. It's a gamble that pays off if the tracker lasts 2+ years." },
      { q: "Which has better tracking accuracy?", a: "The Tractive is more accurate (2-5 meters vs 5-15 meters) and refreshes more frequently. The Tractive's app also shows location history and activity patterns. The No-Fee tracker gives you 'which block is my dog on' level accuracy. For finding a lost dog in a dense neighborhood, Tractive's precision matters. For 'is my dog still in the backyard,' both work." },
      { q: "Can I put either tracker on a cat?", a: "Both work for cats at similar weights (20-26g). The Tractive is more waterproof (IPX7), which matters for outdoor cats. The No-Fee tracker is lighter (20g) but less durable. For indoor/outdoor cats, the Tractive's global coverage is overkill — the No-Fee tracker at $33 is more sensible if your cat stays in your neighborhood." },
    ],
  },
};

const data = compareMap[slug] || compareMap["litter-robot-4-vs-leos-loo-too"];

// Get products from products.json, or use inline data for generic comparisons
const productA = data.productAId ? allProducts.get(data.productAId) : data.productA;
const productB = data.productBId ? allProducts.get(data.productBId) : data.productB;
---

<BaseLayout title={data.title} description={data.description} type="article" publishDate="2026-05-22" modifiedDate="2026-06-03">
  <Breadcrumb crumbs={[{ label: "Compare", href: "/compare/" }, { label: productA.name + " vs " + productB.name }]} />

  <article>
    <h1 class="font-display text-3xl font-bold leading-tight text-forest md:text-4xl">{data.title}</h1>
    <p class="mt-3 text-lg leading-relaxed text-bark-muted">{data.description}</p>

    <!-- Trust line -->
    <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-bark-muted/80 italic">How we compare: We analyze verified owner reviews and product specs — <a href="/about/" class="underline decoration-honey/50 hover:text-honey">learn more about our research process</a></p>

    <Takeaways items={[
      `Winner: ${data.winner.substring(0, 100)}...`,
      `${productA.name} — $${productA.price} | ${productA.rating}★`,
      `${productB.name} — ${typeof productB.price === 'number' ? '$' + productB.price : productB.price} | ${productB.rating}★`,
      `${data.comparisonRows.length} features compared head-to-head`,
    ]} />

    <!-- Bottom Line -->
    <div class="mt-8 rounded-2xl border border-honey/30 bg-honey/5 p-6 md:p-8">
      <p class="text-sm font-semibold uppercase tracking-wider text-honey">Bottom Line</p>
      <p class="mt-2 font-display text-lg italic text-forest">"{data.winner}"</p>
    </div>

    <!-- Side by Side Cards -->
    <div class="mt-10 grid gap-6 md:grid-cols-2">
      {[productA, productB].map((p, idx) => (
        <div class={`rounded-2xl border p-6 ${idx === 0 ? 'border-forest/20 bg-forest/3' : 'border-sage-dark/30 bg-white'}`}>
          <!-- Product image -->
          {p.imageUrl && (
            <img src={p.imageUrl} alt={p.name} class="mb-4 h-48 w-full rounded-xl object-cover bg-sage/60" width="400" height="192" loading="lazy" decoding="async" />
          )}
          <h2 class="font-display text-xl font-bold text-forest">{p.name}</h2>
          <p class="text-sm text-bark-muted">by {p.brand}</p>
          <p class="mt-2 font-display text-3xl font-bold text-forest">{typeof p.price === 'number' ? '$' + p.price : p.price}</p>
          {typeof p.price === 'number' && <p class="text-sm text-bark-muted">~${Math.round(p.price / 36)}/mo over 3 years</p>}
          <div class="mt-4 space-y-2.5 text-sm">
            <p class="font-semibold text-green-800">Pros</p>
            {p.pros.map((pro: string) => <p class="text-green-800/80">&check; {pro}</p>)}
            <p class="mt-2 font-semibold text-rose-dark/80">Cons</p>
            {p.cons.map((con: string) => <p class="text-rose-dark/70">&times; {con}</p>)}
          </div>
          <a href={p.amazonUrl} target="_blank" rel="nofollow sponsored noopener"
             class="mt-5 inline-flex w-full items-center justify-center gap-2 rounded-xl bg-honey py-3 font-bold text-white shadow-sm transition-all hover:bg-honey-dark hover:shadow-md active:scale-[0.98]">
            View on Amazon
            <svg class="h-3.5 w-3.5" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2.5" d="M17 8l4 4m0 0l-4 4m4-4H3"/></svg>
          </a>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>

    <!-- Feature Comparison Table -->
    <div class="mt-10">
      <h2 class="mb-4 font-display text-xl font-bold text-forest">Feature Comparison</h2>
      <div class="overflow-x-auto rounded-2xl border border-sage-dark/30">
        <table class="w-full text-sm">
          <thead>
            <tr class="bg-sage/60">
              <th class="px-5 py-3.5 text-left font-semibold text-forest">Feature</th>
              <th class="px-5 py-3.5 font-semibold text-forest">{productA.name}</th>
              <th class="px-5 py-3.5 font-semibold text-forest">{productB.name}</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody class="divide-y divide-sage-dark/20">
            {data.comparisonRows.map(([feature, a, b]) => (
              <tr class="bg-white transition-colors hover:bg-sage-light/50">
                <td class="px-5 py-3.5 font-medium text-bark">{feature}</td>
                <td class="px-5 py-3.5 text-bark-muted">{a}</td>
                <td class="px-5 py-3.5 text-bark-muted">{b}</td>
              </tr>
            ))}
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>
    </div>

    <FAQ items={data.faqs} />

    <!-- Bottom CTA -->
    <div class="mt-10 rounded-2xl border border-honey/40 bg-gradient-to-br from-honey/5 to-cream p-6 md:p-8">
      <p class="font-display text-xl font-bold text-forest text-center">Which one is right for you?</p>
      <div class="mt-6 grid gap-4 md:grid-cols-2">
        {[productA, productB].map((p) => (
          <a href={p?.amazonUrl || "#"} target="_blank" rel="nofollow sponsored noopener"
             class="flex flex-col items-center rounded-xl border border-sage-dark/30 bg-white p-5 shadow-sm transition-all hover:border-honey/50 hover:shadow-md active:scale-[0.98]">
            <span class="font-semibold text-forest">{p?.name || "Product"}</span>
            <span class="text-sm text-bark-muted">by {p?.brand || ""}</span>
            {p?.price && <span class="mt-1 font-bold text-honey">${p.price}</span>}
            <span class="mt-3 inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 rounded-lg bg-honey px-5 py-2 text-sm font-bold text-white">View on Amazon <svg class="h-3 w-3" fill="none" viewBox="0 0 24 24" stroke="currentColor"><path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2.5" d="M17 8l4 4m0 0l-4 4m4-4H3"/></svg></span>
          </a>
        ))}
      </div>
      <p class="mt-4 text-center text-xs text-bark-muted/70">As an Amazon Associate, we earn from qualifying purchases. <a href="/affiliate-disclosure/" class="underline">Learn more</a></p>
    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
